issue.title: git completion doesn't handle filenames with \r well
issue.body:
fish, version 3.6.1

I know this is a super weird "use case"^^
```
$ mkdir /tmp/test && cd /tmp/test/
$ git init
$ touch foobar\r
$ git add foo<TAB>  # results in this:
$ git add foobar\\r
fatal: pathspec 'foobar\r' did not match any files

# this works
$ git add foobar\r
# or this also works (for some reason?)
$ git add foobar\\\r
```
So the tab completion is adding `\\r` while it probably just should be `\r`

Same it seems with `\n` from a brief test.

Sidenote: Tab completion for e.g. `less foo<TAB>` works correctly, using one backslash instead of two.

comment.body: Ok :sweat_smile: Thanks for looking into this! Hopefully I'll never see a git repo again that has a file like this ;)

comment.body:
I'm going to call this one unfixable as it stands:

We use `git status --porcelain=2`, and without `-z` that escapes things like `\r` on its own. That's not easily reversible in general because we don't really know *what* git escapes or how it escapes it, we can't really throw it into `string unescape`.

And unfortunately with `-z`, ostensibly the option meant for this, it will also start absolutizing paths, which makes it really hard to complete things. That's an awkward coupling of concerns from git's side, but if we have to pick one I'm going to pick the more common one.

That means I'm just going to tell you to not use carriage return in your filenames, sorry.

issue.title: Redirect stderr from inner functions using command substitutions ("subshells")

labels.name: bug
labels.description: Something that's not working as intended

milestone.title: fish-future
milestone.description:
These are issues that are not targeted for an upcoming minor or major release. After a release, we will re-examine these issues and pull any in that we think are good targets; that is retarget them to the next minor (or major) release.

If you can provide a fix for an issue in this milestone, we'll generally accept it for the next release even if the issue is not targeted for the release.

issue.body:
It does not seem to be possible to redirect stderror from inner functions using "subshells".

``` sh
function example_error
  if not contains '-a' b c
    echo 'Not contains'
  else
    echo 'Contains'
  end
end

function example_runner
  set -l result (example_error)
  echo $result
end

example_runner ^/dev/null
```

This will give:

```
contains: Unknown option “b”
/home/terje/test.fish (line 2): if not contains '-a' b c
                                ^
in function “example_error”,
    called on line 10 of file “/home/terje/test.fish”,

in command substitution
    called on line 10 of file “/home/terje/test.fish”,

in function “example_runner”,
    called on line 14 of file “/home/terje/test.fish”,

Not contains
```

There are two different ways to solve this:
Either do the redirection within the subshell `(example_error ^/dev/null)` or wrap everything inside a fish call `fish -c 'example_runner' ^/dev/null`. Neither solution is very good.

comment.body:
I'm not sure if this is the same bug or a different one,
But I wanted to do something like this
```
echo foo >/nonexistent/path 2>/dev/null
```
Where any write error for the redirect get's silenced.
Obviously that doesn't work as the error isn't produced by `echo` but fish itself.
However, I thought these would work:
```
begin; echo foo >/nonexistent/path; end 2>/dev/null
eval "echo foo >/nonexistent/path" 2>/dev/null
```
Which they didn't, and using subshells or functions like the start of this issue suggested doesn't work either. Using `eval` also doesn't work.
The only solution I could get working is to use `fish -c` but I'd rather nat (as I have to then ensure everything I pass to it is properly escaped, and will likely be way slower).

issue.title: completions/git: use `complete -C` for git aliases
issue.body:
## Description

This PR refactors the git completion for aliases. With these changes, completion just works for recursive aliases, and aliased commands are transparently completed as if the alias were resolved.

I made these changes because of issues I was running into with git-branchless and the aliases it sets up. I had set up completion for the `git-branchless` commands which worked correctly, but the completion would not work when using the aliases. I have been using these changes locally for the past few months, and they work great.

comment.diff_hunk:
@@ -737,16 +661,39 @@ function __fish_git_complete_stashes
     __fish_git stash list --format=%gd:%gs 2>/dev/null | string replace ":" \t
 end
 
-function __fish_git_aliases
-    __fish_git config -z --get-regexp '^alias\.' 2>/dev/null | while read -lz key value
-        begin
-            set -l name (string replace -r '^.*\.' '' -- $key)
-            set -l val (string shorten --no-newline -m 36 -- $value)
-            printf "%s\t%s\n" $name "alias: $val"
+function __fish_git_get_aliases
+    # Get valid aliases - aliases for a builtin or custom commands are ignored
+    set -l non_aliases (__fish_git --list-cmds=main,others)
+    __fish_git config --get-regexp '^alias\.' 2>/dev/null | while read -l key value
+        set -l name (string replace -r '^alias\.' '' -- $key)
+        if not contains -- $name $non_aliases
+            printf "%s\t%s\n" $name $value
         end
     end
 end
 
+function __fish_git_complete_aliases
+    # List the defined aliases when completing a command
+    __fish_git_get_aliases | while read -l -d\t name value
+        printf "%s\talias: %s\n" $name (string shorten --no-newline -m 36 -- $value)
+    end
+end
+
+function __fish_git_using_alias
+    # Check whether the current completion is for an alias
+    set -l cmd (__fish_git_needs_command)
+    test -n "$cmd"
+    and contains -- "$cmd" (__fish_git_get_aliases | string split -f 1 \t)
+end
+
+function __fish_git_complete_for_alias
+    # Resolve the alias and complete the command
+    # Assumes that __fish_git_using_alias is true
+    set -l alias (__fish_git_needs_command)
+    set -l value (git config --get "alias.$alias")
+    complete -C (commandline -p | string replace -- "$alias" "$value")
comment.body: You can also see that the tests are failing - this doesn't complete an alias of `re` for `restore --staged` properly, there is some difference.

comment.body:
Oh, also: This will replace the first occurence of whatever characters.

That means if you have an alias "it"... it will replace the "it" in "git". The logic needs to be a good deal more complex:

- Find the subcommand
- Replace *that* with the alias value
- Run *that* via `complete -C`
